[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Maria is 68. Maria has type 2 diabetes that has been getting harder to control, congestive heart failure that landed her in the hospital three months ago, chronic kidney disease at stage 3b that her nephrologist is watching closely, peripheral neuropathy that her podiatrist sees every couple of months, mild cognitive impairment that her neurologist diagnosed last year and that her daughter is watching with growing concern, and the kind of medication list that takes the pharmacist a full minute to read out loud at the counter. Maria has a primary care physician who has been her doctor for twelve years and whom she trusts. Maria also has, currently active in her chart: a cardiologist, a nephrologist, an endocrinologist, a podiatrist, a neurologist, a diabetes educator she sees twice a year, a physical therapist she sees twice a week (or is supposed to), a home-health nurse who comes on Tuesdays, a pharmacist she calls when she has questions, and a hospital case manager who was assigned during her CHF admission three months ago and whose role in Maria's life since discharge is, even Maria is not sure.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Maria's calendar for the past month, which her daughter has started keeping for her on a printed paper grid stuck to the refrigerator with a dolphin-shaped magnet, looks like this. A Monday cardiologist follow-up that got rescheduled twice because the cardiologist's office was renovating their offices and then because the cardiologist's nurse had the flu. A Tuesday lab draw at the cardiologist's request, except the lab order routed to the wrong outpatient lab and Maria sat in the waiting room for forty minutes before someone explained that the order had not arrived. A Wednesday endocrinologist visit where the endocrinologist asked, with the tone of a person who had asked this question before, why Maria's most recent A1c was not in the chart, and Maria had to explain that the lab draw last Tuesday had not happened because of the routing problem. A Thursday physical therapy session that Maria did not go to because her ride had been canceled and the dial-a-ride number had a forty-five-minute hold time. A Friday podiatrist visit which went fine, except that the podiatrist noticed Maria's blood sugar had been running high based on what she could see, and recommended Maria call her endocrinologist, who Maria had just seen on Wednesday, and who Maria did not particularly want to call again. A Saturday pharmacy run where Maria's furosemide refill had not gone through because the prior authorization on her brand-name version had expired and the pharmacist's call to the cardiologist's office had gone to voicemail two days earlier and the office had not yet called back. A Sunday phone call to her daughter at 9 PM because Maria had a question about whether the new pill the cardiologist had prescribed (eplerenone, but Maria called it "the new heart pill") was supposed to be taken with the white pill or the blue pill or before breakfast or after, because the after-visit summary was confusing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is not a complicated patient by the standards of a real care management workflow. This is, in the language of healthcare operations, a "high-needs, high-cost" or "rising-risk" patient. <!-- TODO: verify; the categorization of patients into population segments based on acuity and care complexity (low risk, rising risk, high needs/high cost) is widely used in population-health management; specific definitions and proportions vary by program --> Maria is in approximately the top 5-10% of patients by total care complexity but in the top 50% of patients by total cost. Maria is the kind of patient that the healthcare system, when it works, does well, and when it does not work, does badly in expensive and dangerous ways. Maria is also the kind of patient who, when you ask her how she would describe her care, says "I have lots of doctors. They don't talk to each other. I am the one carrying the messages."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The reason Maria is carrying the messages is that the actual care-coordination infrastructure of American healthcare is held together with a combination of fax machines, semi-structured referral letters, after-visit summary PDFs that are scanned out of one EHR and uploaded into another, phone calls between offices that go to voicemail and never get returned, patient portals that are technically interoperable in the FHIR-based sense but are practically fragmented because each provider lives in a different patient portal and Maria has stopped logging into all but two of them, prior authorization processes that vary by payer and by drug and by procedure, scheduling systems that do not talk to each other, transportation benefits that exist in theory but require sustained effort to actually use, and a care plan that exists only in fragments across multiple providers' notes with no single canonical version. Maria's hospital case manager, when she was on shift, did good work; the case manager's caseload of 60-80 patients meant she could spend roughly fifteen minutes a week on Maria's care coordination after the initial transition-of-care work was done. Maria's primary care physician, who genuinely cares about Maria and remembers her grandchildren's names, has roughly seven minutes to spend with Maria during a follow-up visit and roughly zero minutes to spend on the between-visit coordination work that is the actual problem. The system, in other words, has people who are paid to coordinate Maria's care, and the problem is that the people who are paid to coordinate Maria's care have time to coordinate the care of the most acute portion of their caseload, which means everyone else is doing the coordination work themselves with whoever is willing to help (a daughter, in Maria's case, who is doing it from another state on her lunch breaks).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing about care coordination that surprises engineers when they encounter the problem for the first time is that it is not a missing-data problem in the way that the rest of healthcare's interoperability struggles are. The data exists. The cardiologist's note from the visit two months ago is in a system. The endocrinologist's note is in a system. The lab results are in a system. The home-health nurse's progress notes are in a system. The pharmacy claim history is in a system. The hospital discharge summary is in a system. The prior authorization status is in a system. The referral, with its specific reason and the cardiologist's expected timeframe, is in a system. The problem is that these systems are scattered across multiple organizational boundaries (the primary care practice, the cardiology specialty group, the hospital health system, the pharmacy benefit manager, the medical insurer, the home-health agency, the durable-medical-equipment supplier), each system has its own conventions, each system charges for or restricts access to its data, and the integrations that exist between them are partial, asynchronous, and often human-mediated. What Maria's care actually needs, on a Tuesday at 2:30 PM when she is wondering whether she should worry about her swollen ankles, is for someone or something to: pull together the threads of her care plan from all of those systems, surface the relevant context from each, recognize whether the swollen ankles are explainable by her recent eplerenone start (and therefore something her cardiologist is likely to anticipate) or whether they suggest a CHF decompensation (which would warrant a same-day call to the cardiologist or a same-day visit to the office), and either reassure Maria with explainable evidence or route her to the right human at the right level of urgency. That is what care coordination is, and that is what is currently happening in the heads of overworked case managers and in the collective effort of patients and their families. <!-- TODO: verify; care coordination as defined by the Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality (AHRQ) and the National Quality Forum includes the deliberate organization of patient care activities and information sharing across all participants in care to facilitate the appropriate delivery of healthcare services, with multiple validated frameworks for measurement and intervention -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The previous wave of care-coordination tools tried to solve this problem with case-management software (largely successful at supporting professional case managers but not at scale-extending the case management to the broader rising-risk population), with patient portals (largely failed at the coordination layer because each portal lives in one provider's data world), with care management programs run by health plans (helpful for the highest-risk segment but bound by the same caseload constraints as in-clinic case management), and with health information exchanges (genuinely helpful for the data-sharing layer but not the synthesis layer; an HIE will tell you that Maria has data in seven systems, but it will not assemble Maria's care plan for you). The conversational AI layer is the first wave of technology that has a real shot at the synthesis-and-presentation problem at scale, because a tool-using LLM with appropriate integration to the underlying systems can do the synthesis work for the rising-risk population that, today, only happens for the highest-risk segment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This recipe is about that bot. It is not a replacement for a human care manager; the patient population that needs coordination support is far larger than the population that can be served by human care managers under realistic caseloads, and the bot exists to extend the reach of the care management team to the rising-risk segment that is currently not getting coordination support at all. It is also not a clinical decision-making tool in the symptom-checker sense; it does not tell Maria whether her swollen ankles are CHF decompensation, but it does pull together the recent eplerenone start, the most recent weight from the home scale, the cardiologist's note that anticipated some lower-extremity edema during titration, the patient-reported symptom, and the recommendation from the cardiologist's care plan that "if weight gain exceeds 3 pounds in 2 days, call the office," and either tells Maria the situation matches the anticipated picture (in which case "here is what to watch for, here is when to call your cardiologist") or routes her to a human care manager (in which case the human gets the synthesized context already loaded). The bot's central value proposition is the same as recipe 11.7 (chronic disease coaching) for the medical-management piece, but the integration surface is much wider and the workflow integration is much deeper, because care coordination is, by its nature, a multi-system problem.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few things this recipe is and is not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is the assistant that helps Maria (and her daughter, with appropriate consent) navigate the actual care-coordination layer: tracking pending referrals, surfacing the latest after-visit summary in plain language, confirming or revising upcoming appointments, surfacing prior authorization status, surfacing transportation benefits, supporting medication reconciliation across providers, surfacing the patient's care plan as a single coherent document, surfacing care-transition checklists (post-discharge follow-up, post-procedure recovery), routing to the appropriate human care manager when the situation calls for one, and serving as a single conversational entry point for "what's happening with my care."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a clinical-decision-making tool. The bot does not tell Maria whether her ankles are decompensating. The bot does not adjust her medications. The bot does not interpret her labs in a clinical sense. The bot routes the clinical questions to the right human, with appropriate context attached.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a replacement for the human care management team. The bot extends the team's reach by handling the routine coordination layer for a much larger population than the team could cover directly, and by surfacing higher-acuity situations to the team with synthesized context. The bot is the team's assistant, not the team's replacement.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a single-EHR product. The bot's value proposition specifically requires multi-system integration: the patient's primary care EHR, specialty practice EHRs (which are often different from the primary EHR), the hospital EHR (which is often different again), the pharmacy benefit manager's data, the medical insurer's data (especially for prior authorization status), the home-health agency's records, the durable-medical-equipment supplier's records, and any HIE the institution participates in. Building this without taking the multi-system integration seriously produces a coordination assistant that can only coordinate the parts of care that are inside one organization's walls, which is most of the bot's value gone.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a wallet-and-portal aggregator. There are products in the consumer health space that aggregate data across portals for individual patients; the architecture in this recipe is institutional, deployed by a payer, an integrated delivery network, an ACO, or a large health system, with the institution's care management team as the human backstop and the institution's compliance posture covering the data flows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a quick win. The deployment timeline is measured in quarters and years. The integration work is substantial; each integration with a specialty practice's EHR, each integration with a payer's prior authorization API, each integration with a transportation benefit, each integration with a home-health agency is its own multi-month project. The conversational layer is the easier part. The institutional commitment to building and maintaining the integration surface is the central commitment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is also the recipe in this chapter where the right deployment, when it works, has the largest visible impact on patients. Maria's daughter, who has spent two years coordinating Maria's care from another state, gets a tool that turns a five-hour weekly effort into a ten-minute weekly effort. Maria, who has been carrying the messages, gets the messages carried. The bot does not solve American healthcare's care-coordination problem; the structural problems are upstream of any technology. But for the specific patient in front of you, on the specific Tuesday at 2:30 PM when she is wondering about her ankles, the bot can be the difference between a confused patient who eventually gives up and a patient who gets her question answered with reassurance or routed to the right human with the right context. That is worth building.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Let's get into it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
