[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: Conversational Assistance Over a Multi-System Care-Coordination Substrate
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why Care Coordination Has Been the Hardest Workflow to Digitize
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Care coordination, as a clinical workflow, sits at the intersection of every other healthcare workflow. It depends on the EHR, on the scheduling system, on the referral management system, on the prior authorization system, on the pharmacy benefit, on the medical benefit, on the home-health agency, on the DME supplier, on transportation benefits, on social services, and on the patient's own household. The reason it has resisted digitization is not that any one of these systems is hard to interface with; it is that the integration of all of them into a single coherent picture of "what is happening with this patient's care" is structurally hard. Each system has its own data model, its own update cadence, its own reliability profile, its own access conventions, its own patient-matching approach, and its own incentives around sharing data. The HIE layer that was supposed to solve this in the 2010s did not solve it; it created a substrate for raw data exchange but did not create the synthesis layer. The patient portal layer that was supposed to solve this with consumer-facing interfaces did not solve it; each portal is anchored to one provider's data world, and patients with care across multiple providers end up with five portals and one paper grid stuck to the refrigerator.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A care coordination workflow, in the operational sense that case managers do it, is roughly the following loop. Pull the relevant context for this patient: active care plan, open referrals, upcoming appointments, recent encounter notes, recent labs, recent medications, recent prior authorization actions, recent claims, recent home-health notes, social-determinant flags. Identify the gaps and the loose ends: referrals that have not been scheduled, appointments that were missed, lab orders that have not been completed, prior authorizations that are pending, medication discrepancies across providers, transportation gaps for upcoming visits, social-determinant concerns that intersect with the medical plan. Produce or update a care-coordination work list: actions for the case manager (call the cardiologist's office about the prior auth), actions for the patient (schedule the lab draw, call the dial-a-ride number), actions for the care team (the primary care physician should know the cardiologist added eplerenone). Route those actions to the people who can do them. Track the actions through to closure. Repeat. Case managers do this manually, with whatever tooling their case-management software supports, with phone calls and faxes and EHR messages and patient outreach. Good case managers do it well; the problem is operational, in the sense that case management capacity is bounded by FTE count and caseload size, and the population that needs coordination is much larger than the case management workforce can cover.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing that changed the workflow shape is, as in the rest of chapter 11, large language models with tool-use that can carry a coherent multi-turn conversation, plus the maturity of the underlying integration surface (FHIR APIs are now widely available, payers expose prior authorization status APIs more often than they did five years ago, home-health agencies have web-services interfaces, and HIEs increasingly support FHIR-based queries). The bot is not a case manager; the bot is a conversational interface to the synthesis layer that case managers do in their heads. A patient asking "what's happening with my referral to the cardiologist?" gets, instead of "log into the patient portal and look in the messaging center," an actual answer: the referral was placed on the 12th, the cardiology office received it on the 14th, an appointment was offered on the 22nd which the patient declined because of a transportation conflict, the office is awaiting a callback to reschedule, and the prior authorization for the planned echocardiogram is approved through the end of next month. The bot pulled this from four different systems, synthesized it, and presented it. The case manager, who would have done the same synthesis manually, can spend her time on the harder parts of her caseload.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A note on what care-coordination conversational AI is and is not, because the category is conflated. The thing this recipe describes is a synthesis-and-presentation assistant with tool-using access to the patient's care-coordination substrate. The thing it is not is a chatbot that answers benefits questions in a vacuum (that is recipe 11.5), a chatbot that handles symptom triage (that is recipe 11.6), or a chatbot that delivers chronic disease coaching content (that is recipe 11.7). The care coordination assistant overlaps with all of these and integrates with them in a fully realized deployment, but its central function is the multi-system synthesis layer that none of the others provide.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What a Care Coordination Assistant Actually Does
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A care coordination assistant, as designed in this recipe, is a tool-using LLM with a system prompt that tells it which assistant it is, the patient's authenticated context (active conditions, current medications, allergies, recent encounters, recent labs, recent imaging, active referrals, upcoming appointments, the patient's care plan if one is consolidated, prior authorization actions, claims activity, home-health activity, DME activity, social-determinant flags, the assigned care team and their roles, the patient's stated preferences and consent posture for cross-organization sharing), access to a structured library of care-coordination playbooks and patient-facing educational content, and a careful set of tools for retrieving data from each integrated system, surfacing actions to the patient, routing to the appropriate human care team member, generating care-team alerts, and logging coordination events.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The conversation surface, like the chronic disease coach in 11.7, is a stream of conversational episodes rather than a single conversation. The bot is patient-initiated for most interactions ("what's happening with my referral?", "do I have a lab draw this week?", "I lost my prescription bottle and I cannot remember the dose"), bot-initiated for specific care-plan-driven prompts ("your follow-up with cardiology is in three days; here are the things you may want to bring up"), event-initiated for care-coordination signals ("a new referral was placed for you yesterday; here is what it is for and what to expect"), and human-initiated when the care team uses the bot as a delivery channel for coordination work ("your care manager Adriana has a question about whether you've been able to schedule the home health visit").
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The bot's task surface decomposes roughly as follows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Onboarding and consent.** The patient is enrolled in the care-coordination program by their care team or self-enrolls through their payer or institution. The consent flow specifically covers cross-organization data sharing (the bot pulls data from organizations beyond the enrolling institution; the patient's consent is required for that aggregation), care-team sharing (which clinicians on the patient's care team can see the bot's interactions and synthesized work product), proxy access (whether the patient's daughter or other proxy can interact with the bot on the patient's behalf), and the privacy posture for the synthesized care record itself (which is, structurally, a new clinical artifact that did not exist before the bot aggregated it).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care plan synthesis and presentation.** The bot maintains a synthesized version of the patient's care plan drawing from the institution's CarePlan FHIR resource, the specialty providers' care plans where accessible, the hospital discharge summary's transition-of-care plan, and the home-health agency's plan of care. The synthesis is presented to the patient in plain language ("here is what each of your providers is asking you to do this month"), with appropriate caveats when the synthesis is uncertain. The patient can ask for the next-step view ("what should I do this week?"), the by-condition view ("what is the plan for my CHF?"), or the by-provider view ("what is my cardiologist asking?"). The synthesis is also surfaced to the care team for review and refinement.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Referral tracking and status surfacing.** The bot tracks each open referral from placement through completion, surfacing the current status (placed, transmitted, received, scheduled, completed, results returned), the expected timeline, the patient's role at each step (does the patient need to call to schedule, or is the office calling them?), and the prior authorization status if applicable. When a referral is stuck (no scheduling activity, missing prior auth, missed appointment), the bot surfaces it to the patient with an action ("you have a referral to cardiology that has not been scheduled yet; would you like me to try to help you schedule it, or transfer you to your care manager?") and to the care team for awareness.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Appointment and transportation coordination.** The bot surfaces upcoming appointments across providers, identifies conflicts and overlaps, surfaces transportation needs ahead of time, integrates with the patient's transportation benefit (where applicable) to schedule rides, and helps with rescheduling when conflicts arise. The bot does not unilaterally reschedule clinical visits; rescheduling routes through scheduling-bot integration (recipe 11.2) or through the appropriate office.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Medication reconciliation across providers.** The bot maintains an aggregated view of the patient's medications drawing from the EHR, the pharmacy claims, the home medication list the patient confirms, and the specialty providers' medication lists where accessible. Discrepancies (the cardiologist added eplerenone; the primary care chart does not yet reflect it; the pharmacy claim shows the fill last Saturday) are surfaced for the patient and for the care team. The bot does not adjust medications; medication adjustments route through prescribing-physician workflow.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Prior authorization status tracking.** The bot surfaces the status of pending prior authorizations: which medication or procedure, which payer, which date submitted, which expected decision timeline, and what to do if a denial occurs. Where the institution has access to a payer's prior authorization API, the bot pulls live status; where the institution does not, the bot surfaces the most recent known status with appropriate caveats.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care transition support.** The bot provides structured support during care transitions (hospital-to-home is the most consequential, with also primary care to specialist, primary care to home health, primary care to hospice, primary care to long-term care). The transition-support pattern is a structured checklist appropriate to the transition type (hospital-to-home: medication reconciliation, follow-up appointment within seven days, equipment delivery confirmation, home-health start-of-care confirmation, red-flag symptom education, transportation arrangement) with the bot tracking completion, surfacing gaps, and routing to the care team when gaps require human intervention.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **After-visit summary translation.** The bot retrieves the after-visit summary from a recent visit and presents it to the patient in plain language with a focus on what to do next (the to-do list embedded in the summary, often buried in clinical prose), what to watch for (red-flag symptoms the clinician noted), and when the next contact is expected. This is the conversational adaptation of recipe 2.5 with care-coordination context.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-provider message handling.** The bot acts as a conversational front-end to the patient's messages with their care team, routing messages to the appropriate provider, supporting the patient in formulating clear messages, and surfacing message history. The bot does not impersonate clinicians and does not generate messages that purport to be from clinicians; it supports the patient in communicating with them.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team alert generation and routing.** When the bot identifies a coordination gap, a clinical signal that requires escalation, or a patient need beyond the bot's scope, it generates a structured alert to the appropriate human care team member with synthesized context. The routing logic depends on the alert type: clinical signals (potential CHF decompensation, lab values out of range, medication adherence concerns) route to the patient's clinician; coordination gaps (referral stuck, prior auth denied, transportation problem) route to the care manager; social-determinant concerns (food insecurity disclosed, housing instability disclosed) route to the care manager and (with consent) to a community-health worker or social worker.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Long-term relationship maintenance.** Like the chronic disease coach, the care coordination assistant maintains conversation history and stated patient preferences across many months and years. The relationship is functional rather than companion-flavored; the bot does not simulate friendship or affection. The bot acknowledges prior context appropriately ("last month we worked on getting your transportation benefit set up; how has that been going?") in ways that support continuity without simulating personhood.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team feedback integration.** The bot receives feedback from the care team about specific interactions: the care manager flags a bot response as inappropriate for review; the primary care physician marks a bot-generated alert as actioned; the cardiologist requests a change to the patient's care plan that the bot picks up on next refresh.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why a Generic LLM Cannot Run a Care Coordination Assistant
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A naive product approach would be: take a generalist LLM, give it a chat surface, give it tool-use access to one or two underlying systems, and let it answer coordination questions. This breaks in several specific ways.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of multi-system synthesis.** A bot with access to one system (the institution's EHR) can answer questions about data in that system. The patient's care coordination problem is, by definition, the synthesis problem across systems. A bot that says "you do not have a referral to cardiology" because the institution's EHR does not show one, while the cardiology specialty practice's EHR shows the patient was seen there last month, is not solving the coordination problem. The architecture requires deliberate integration with each system the patient has data in, with patient consent for cross-organization synthesis, and with a synthesis layer that combines the data into a coherent picture.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of data freshness and reliability.** Different systems update at different cadences with different reliability. The EHR encounter note may be available within hours of the visit; the specialty practice's note may take days to flow back. The pharmacy claim is typically available within a day or two; the prescription fill itself may not be. The prior authorization status may be live (with API access) or may be days out of date (with batch updates). The bot needs to know the freshness of each data source and to communicate uncertainty when relying on stale data ("based on what I see, your prior auth was approved on the 15th; the data is from the 20th, so if anything has changed since then it may not be reflected here").
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of coordination-action sequencing.** A patient referral has a multi-step lifecycle that depends on which step is currently active and which actions are appropriate from each role. A referral that has just been placed needs the receiving practice to receive and triage it; the patient role at this stage is to wait. A referral that has been received but not scheduled needs the patient or the receiving practice to schedule; the patient role is to call (or wait for a call). A referral that has been scheduled needs the patient to attend and (often) to obtain prior authorization for any planned procedures; the patient role is preparation. The bot's responses are different at each step, and the model needs the structured knowledge of where in the lifecycle each referral is.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of care-team-role-appropriate routing.** Different coordination problems route to different team members. A clinical question routes to the patient's clinician. A coordination gap routes to the care manager. A social-determinant concern routes to the care manager and a social worker or community health worker. A billing question routes to the billing department. A benefits question routes to the benefits navigator or to the payer. The bot's routing logic encodes the institution's care-team structure; a generalist LLM does not know it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model invents data when grounding is weak.** A bot freestyling answers about a patient's care coordination, when the underlying data is missing or stale, will sometimes produce confident-sounding answers that are wrong. A patient who is told "your prior authorization for eplerenone was approved" when in fact it was denied is going to discover the discrepancy at the pharmacy counter, with appropriate consequences for trust. The bot must ground every factual answer in a cited tool-call result with version stamping, and must say "I don't see clear data on that; let me connect you with your care manager" when the grounding is not clean.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of consent and proxy access.** A patient may have given consent for cross-organization data aggregation and for proxy access by their daughter; a patient may not have given consent for either. The bot must enforce the patient's consent posture at the data-retrieval level (do not pull data the patient has not consented to aggregate), at the conversation level (do not surface information the patient has not consented to share with this proxy), and at the routing level (do not generate care-team alerts that share information beyond the consent scope). A generalist LLM does not enforce these.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when not to act.** A patient asking "can you reschedule my cardiologist appointment?" is asking the bot to take an action with real-world consequences. The bot's policy on which actions are auto-callable and which require human approval is institutionally specified. Some institutions allow the bot to reschedule routine follow-ups directly via scheduling-API integration; many institutions require a human in the loop for any clinical-visit rescheduling. The bot encodes the policy explicitly; the generalist LLM does not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of multi-system patient matching.** The patient is "Maria Rodriguez" in the primary care EHR, "Maria Rodriguez-Chen" in the cardiology EHR (where she went by her hyphenated name during a brief period in the early 2010s), "M. Rodriguez" with a slightly different DOB in the home-health agency's records, and "Maria R" in the dial-a-ride system. The patient-matching layer (recipes from chapter 5) operates underneath the care coordination assistant; the bot trusts the matching layer's output but logs uncertainty when the matching layer reports low confidence.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of compliance scope across organizational boundaries.** The patient's data crosses HIPAA-covered-entity boundaries (the primary care practice, the specialty practices, the hospital, the payer). Each cross-boundary data flow is governed by a Business Associate Agreement, by HIPAA's TPO (Treatment, Payment, Operations) provisions, by 42 CFR Part 2 where substance-use treatment data is involved, by 21st Century Cures Act information-blocking provisions, and by state-specific data-sharing rules. <!-- TODO: verify; HIPAA TPO provisions, 42 CFR Part 2, 21st Century Cures Act information-blocking provisions, and state-specific health-data-sharing rules govern cross-organization data flows in care coordination contexts; specific compliance obligations vary by deployment --> The bot's architectural posture explicitly enforces these boundaries; a generalist LLM does not know they exist.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of care-team-coverage gaps.** The patient's primary care office is closed at 2:30 PM on Tuesday because the practice has a half-day on Tuesdays. The cardiologist's office is closed at 12 PM on Wednesdays. The care manager is on vacation this week. The bot's coverage logic accounts for who is actually available right now and routes accordingly; the after-hours behavior is different from the in-hours behavior; the on-call coverage path is integrated. A generalist LLM has no theory of staffing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when to escalate to a human care manager.** A coordination question can be handled directly. A clinical question routes to the clinician. A coordination problem that requires advocacy (the prior auth was denied; the patient needs to file an appeal) requires a human care manager. The bot's escalation logic is institutionally specified, with thresholds for auto-escalation (any clinical signal suggesting deterioration; any patient request for a human; any out-of-scope question; any low-confidence handling) and for proactive surfacing (specific patterns that may not feel acute to the patient but that the care team would want to see).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of social-determinant disclosures.** A patient who mentions in passing that they have not been able to afford their copays, that they have lost their housing, that they are food insecure, that they are caring for a sick spouse, that they are experiencing intimate partner violence: each of these is a clinically relevant disclosure that should flow to the care management team and (with consent) to a social worker or community health worker. The bot recognizes these disclosures and routes appropriately; the generalist LLM may handle them as sympathetic chatter without surfacing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of caregiver and proxy interactions.** Many high-needs patients have a family caregiver who interacts with the bot on the patient's behalf, with appropriate proxy authorization. The proxy's questions ("how is my mother's referral going?") are different from the patient's questions ("how is my referral going?") and may have different consent boundaries (the patient may have consented to share their care with a specific proxy but not to discuss specific topics like mental health). The bot's authentication, identity-verification, and consent-enforcement layers handle proxy access explicitly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of cost.** A patient asking "how much will my cardiologist follow-up cost?" is asking a question that depends on the patient's plan, their deductible status, the visit type, the contracted rate, and any prior-payment activity. The benefits-navigator integration (recipe 11.5) handles this, but the care-coordination bot needs to know when to delegate to it and how to surface the answer in care-coordination context.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What the Care Coordination Assistant Has To Do That the Previous Bots Did Not
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Recipes 11.1 through 11.8 established the conversational-AI patterns this recipe inherits: input safety screening with continuous emergency screening, identity verification, tool-use orchestration, output safety screening, audit logging, per-cohort monitoring, scope discipline, prompt-injection defense, graceful degradation, longitudinal-context loading, citation grounding. The care coordination assistant adds eight structural commitments those recipes did not have.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-system integration with explicit data-source-freshness tracking.** The bot integrates with multiple EHRs, the payer's prior authorization API, pharmacy systems, home-health systems, transportation systems, and HIE feeds. Each integration is engineered as a first-class component with health monitoring, freshness tracking, and degraded-mode behavior when the integration is down. The bot communicates uncertainty when relying on stale data.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-plan synthesis with discrepancy surfacing.** The bot maintains a synthesized view of the patient's care plan across providers and surfaces discrepancies. The synthesis is reviewed by the care management team and treated as a clinical artifact with appropriate compliance scope. Skip the synthesis layer and the bot is a thin layer over multiple systems rather than a coordination assistant.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Referral lifecycle awareness.** The bot tracks each referral through its lifecycle and provides stage-appropriate responses. The stage information requires either dedicated referral-management-system integration or careful inference from EHR signals; institutions usually invest in the dedicated integration for serious deployments.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-organization consent enforcement.** The bot enforces the patient's consent posture for cross-organization data aggregation, proxy access, care-team sharing, and category-specific privacy (mental-health and substance-use data have separate consent considerations). The consent is collected explicitly, is revocable, and is operationally enforced at every data-retrieval and routing decision.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team-role-appropriate routing.** The bot encodes the institution's care-team structure (primary care physician, specialists, care manager, social worker, community health worker, pharmacist, billing department, benefits navigator) and routes appropriately. The routing logic is reviewed by clinical leadership and operations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-transition discipline.** The bot supports specific care transitions with structured checklists, transition-window tracking, and gap-surfacing. The post-discharge transition window is the most consequential and requires the most careful design.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Action-execution policy.** The bot's policy on which actions are auto-callable and which require human approval is institutionally specified, with audit logging on every action-execution event.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Operational integration with the human care management team.** The bot's outputs feed the care management team's workflow tooling (case-management software). The care team's actions feed back into the bot's context. The integration is bidirectional and is a primary architectural concern, not an afterthought.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The rest is largely the same as the previous chapter 11 recipes: tool-surface contract management, identity-assurance lifecycle, conversation logging, scope filtering, per-cohort monitoring, graceful degradation when upstream systems fail.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Care-Coordination Reality
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few notes on what makes care coordination specifically harder than the other patient-facing bot use cases.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The integration surface is the project.** The conversational AI part of the care coordination assistant is the smaller part of the work. The larger part is the integration with each system the patient's data lives in. Each integration is its own multi-month project with the system owner, with negotiation around data-sharing scope, BAA terms, technical interface, refresh cadence, and ongoing operations. Institutions deploying the assistant either commit to the integration work or commit to a narrowed scope where the assistant only covers the systems the institution already has access to. The scope-narrowed version is a reasonable starting point but should be deployed honestly: "this assistant can answer questions about your care at our institution; for care at other providers we will help you connect with them."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Data quality is a long-term commitment, not a one-time clean.** Every integrated system has data quality issues that surface as the assistant's responses are evaluated. The cardiologist's office's EHR has the wrong phone number for the patient. The pharmacy's record shows a medication the patient stopped taking three months ago. The home-health agency's record has an old start-of-care date. The bot is a magnifier of data quality problems, because it surfaces them in patient-facing form. The data-stewardship work that the institution does (or does not do) determines the assistant's apparent quality. Institutions building the assistant typically invest in upstream data-quality work as part of the project.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient matching across organizations is the substrate.** The bot's value depends on correctly matching the patient across systems. The patient-matching layer (chapter 5) operates beneath the assistant; the assistant trusts the matching layer's output but logs match-confidence and uses the confidence in its uncertainty communication. Match failures are a source of incorrect responses; the institutional patient-matching investment is, indirectly, an investment in the assistant's quality.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The patient is often (a) confused, (b) in pain, (c) dealing with cognitive impairment, (d) receiving information from a caregiver, or (e) all of the above.** Care coordination support is most needed by patients whose cognitive or emotional bandwidth is most strained. The assistant's communication design needs to accommodate this. Plain language. Short responses. Clear next-step framing. Careful pacing. Patient-experience design with input from the actual high-needs patient population is non-negotiable.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Caregiver and proxy interactions are not edge cases; they are the dominant interaction pattern for the highest-needs population.** A substantial fraction of high-needs patients have a family caregiver who interacts with the healthcare system on the patient's behalf, often more often than the patient does. The proxy authentication, the proxy consent posture, and the proxy-versus-patient interaction-style adaptation are core architectural concerns. Skip these and the bot is unusable for the population it should be serving best.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team caseload is a bounded resource.** The bot's value comes in part from extending the reach of the care management team to patients the team cannot directly serve. If the bot generates care-team alerts faster than the care management team can absorb them, the team is overwhelmed and the alert system is ignored. The alert-generation calibration is a critical operational concern: too aggressive and the team is overwhelmed; too conservative and the bot is missing alertable situations. The institutional caseload-versus-alert calibration is reviewed regularly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The assistant is a discovery vector for systemic problems.** As the bot operates, it surfaces patterns: a particular specialty practice has consistently long scheduling times; a particular payer denies a particular prior auth more often than expected; a particular care transition has consistently poor follow-up rates. These are operational findings that the institution can act on. The institution that treats the bot as a discovery instrument as well as a patient-facing tool gets disproportionate value from the deployment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-organization cooperation is slow.** Each new specialty practice integration, each new payer integration, each new home-health agency integration involves negotiation. Some organizations are eager partners; some are reluctant; some are technically incapable of providing the integration the bot needs. The institutional patience for the cross-organization work is a precondition for the deployment's success.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The bot's own outputs become a clinical artifact.** The synthesized care plan, the synthesized referral status, the synthesized medication list, the cross-organization conversation log: all of this is a new clinical artifact that did not exist before the bot aggregated it. The compliance posture for the artifact, the retention rules, the patient-access rights, the medical-record-incorporation question: each of these is a deliberate institutional decision.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome demonstration is a multi-year proposition.** A care coordination assistant's impact on metrics like 30-day readmissions, total cost of care, patient experience, and care-team workload is demonstrable over quarters and years, not over weeks. Institutions launching with weekly engagement metrics and expecting outcome attribution within a quarter will be disappointed. The right framing is operational improvement (care manager caseload extended, patient-portal-message volume reduced, no-show rate reduced) on the short horizon and outcome correlation on the long horizon.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Liability exposure is real but is concentrated in specific failure modes.** The bot is not a clinical-decision tool; it does not adjust medications or interpret labs. The bot's liability exposure comes from cases where it incorrectly tells a patient something is fine when it is not (and the patient does not pursue the issue), or where it incorrectly routes a clinical signal away from a clinician. The institutional design discipline is to default conservatively (route to the care team when in doubt; do not provide reassurance without grounding; surface red-flag symptoms even when the patient did not ask).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Where the Field Has Moved
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few practical updates worth knowing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **FHIR APIs are now the table-stakes integration interface for healthcare data.** The 21st Century Cures Act information-blocking provisions, combined with the ONC's certification requirements, have made FHIR R4 APIs widely available across major EHR vendors. <!-- TODO: verify; the 21st Century Cures Act and ONC's Trusted Exchange Framework and Common Agreement (TEFCA) have driven widespread FHIR R4 API availability across major U.S. EHR vendors, with ongoing maturation of the API surface --> Many specialty practices' EHRs now expose FHIR R4 APIs by default. The integration work is still substantial, but the per-system integration is standardized in a way it was not five years ago.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Da Vinci Project profiles for prior authorization.** The HL7 Da Vinci Project has produced FHIR profiles for prior authorization (PAS, CRD, DTR) that some payers now support. <!-- TODO: verify; the HL7 Da Vinci Project has produced implementation guides for Prior Authorization Support (PAS), Coverage Requirements Discovery (CRD), and Documentation Templates and Rules (DTR) that some payers and providers have implemented; adoption varies --> Where supported, the bot can pull prior auth status via standardized API; where not supported, the bot uses the payer's proprietary API or the institution's manual-tracking system.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **TEFCA and QHINs.** The Trusted Exchange Framework and Common Agreement (TEFCA), implemented through Qualified Health Information Networks (QHINs), provides a national-scale framework for cross-organization data exchange. <!-- TODO: verify; TEFCA implementation, the QHIN designation process, and the operational maturity of cross-QHIN exchange continue to evolve since the framework's launch --> Institutions deploying the care coordination assistant can use QHIN-based queries as part of the cross-organization data layer.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Payer-provider data exchange APIs.** Many payers now expose member-data APIs (claims history, prior authorization status, eligibility, member-services activity) that the assistant can integrate with. The Davinci Member Data Exchange profiles are increasingly supported. <!-- TODO: verify; payer-provider data exchange APIs and Da Vinci member-data profiles have grown in adoption since 2023, with ongoing variation in coverage and quality across payers -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Tool-using LLMs handle multi-system synthesis well when grounded carefully.** The function-calling pattern from the previous chapter 11 recipes maps to care coordination. The LLM produces tool calls that retrieve data from each integrated system, synthesizes the results, and presents them with citations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-management-software vendors are increasingly adding conversational interfaces.** Several major case-management-software vendors offer conversational AI overlays that integrate with their existing case-management workflow. <!-- TODO: verify; care management software vendors including Salesforce Health Cloud, Epic, Oracle Health, and others have added conversational AI capabilities of varying maturity, with healthcare-specific adaptations of more general LLM platforms --> Most major institutions deploying in this space run a hybrid: build the orchestration layer in-house, partner with vendors for the case-management-workflow integration, and integrate with the institution's existing care-team tooling.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Hybrid AI-plus-human deployment is the standard.** As with the chronic disease coach and the mental health bot, the dominant pattern is AI for routine coordination plus human care manager for clinical complexity, advocacy work, and high-acuity escalation. The evidence base for hybrid deployments is stronger than for AI-only deployments; institutions launching AI-only care coordination at scale are unlikely to succeed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Equity and access disparities are an active concern.** Care coordination needs are highest in populations with the most fragmented care: low-income patients, racial and ethnic minorities, rural patients, patients with limited English proficiency, patients with disabilities, older adults with cognitive impairment, patients in unstable housing. The bot's per-cohort monitoring needs to track these populations explicitly, because they are simultaneously the populations who most need the support and the populations for whom digital tools have historically underperformed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Build-vs-buy is mature for some segments.** Several mature commercial vendors offer care-coordination software with conversational interfaces at health-plan and integrated-delivery-network scale. Most major institutions deploying in this space run a hybrid: build a thin orchestration layer in-house, partner with vendors for case-management workflow integration and (sometimes) for cross-organization integrations, and integrate with the institution's care-management, telehealth, and clinical-record infrastructure.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
